# Project Nirantara

An edge-native telemetry and messaging infrastructure written in C11. The immediate
workload is a multiplayer gaming backend (~5K concurrent users). Every architectural
decision is made with **connected vehicle telematics** as the primary long-term target.

## Strategic Goals
- Validate edge buffering + store-and-forward patterns under a real workload
- Produce a reusable C networking library (mTLS + MQTT) portable to embedded Linux
- Generate a connected vehicle telemetry pipeline proposal backed by a working prototype

## Repository Layout

```
lib/nirantara-net/   # Reusable C networking library (the core deliverable)
  include/nirantara/ #   Public API headers
  src/               #   Implementations
edge/                # Edge node sync agent (Mosquitto subscriber + SQLite + Postgres sync)
flutter/             # Flutter FFI bindings to nirantara-net
tools/ca/            # CA setup scripts
tools/test/          # Load simulators and test harnesses
docs/                # Architecture documentation
```

## Component Responsibilities

| Component | Owns | Does NOT own |
|-----------|------|--------------|
| nirantara-net | TLS context, mTLS MQTT, CSR/enrollment, key generation | Business logic, routing, DB |
| edge agent | SQLite buffering, MQTT subscription, Postgres sync | Client auth, TLS |
| Mosquitto | mTLS broker, topic routing | Event persistence |
| Postgres (cloud) | Authoritative state, reporting | Edge buffering |

## Key Invariants
- The nirantara-net library MUST compile on ARM Linux (Cortex-A target) without modification
- Private keys NEVER leave the device / secure enclave
- The edge agent MUST handle Mosquitto restart without data loss (SQLite WAL)
- All sync to Postgres is idempotent (upsert, not insert)
